# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
<overview>
<p>The WK-1000 Stratos is Wakazashi Enterprises' entry into the commercial airliner market, designed to compete with Avanti Aerospace's dominant ACL-800 Comet. Unlike other Comet imitators that relied on licensing agreements or outright theft of Avanti's designs, Wakazashi developed the Stratos as an independent effort to match the ACL-800's specifications using Combine-sourced components and engineering. The result is a ninety-passenger airliner that, while smaller than the Comet, represents an honest attempt to challenge Avanti's near-monopoly on quality commercial air travel within the borders of the Draconis Combine. Wakazashi's corporate reputation as one of the Combine's premier aerospace manufacturers lent the Stratos immediate credibility in a market skeptical of foreign designs.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Stratos carries ninety passengers compared to the Comet's one hundred and twenty, a concession to the realities of designing without access to Avanti's proprietary AA-700 propulsion system. Wakazashi compensated by optimizing the aircraft's interior layout for efficiency, ensuring that the smaller passenger count does not translate to a proportionally smaller revenue stream. The Stratos offers a comfortable cabin with amenities competitive with the Comet's economy configuration, though it lacks the expansive first-class suites that define the ACL-800's upper deck. Wakazashi's own turbofan engines provide reliable performance, if not quite the refinement of the Avanti powerplants.</p><p>Where the Stratos gains ground against the Comet is in operational simplicity and maintenance. Wakazashi designed the aircraft with the Combine's existing aerospace maintenance infrastructure in mind, using standardized components that any licensed Wakazashi service center can repair or replace. This reduces downtime between flights and keeps operating costs predictable for the airlines that depend on the aircraft for daily revenue service.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Stratos finds its primary market within the Draconis Combine, where Wakazashi's extensive corporate network ensures ready access to parts and maintenance support. Airlines and planetary transit authorities across the Combine operate the WK-1000 on domestic routes, valuing its Combine-built pedigree and the independence from Avanti supply chains that it represents. Some Stratos airliners have found buyers in the Free Worlds League and Periphery states seeking a quality airliner without the political complications of purchasing from Steiner or Davion manufacturers.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Wakazashi Enterprises' decision to develop the Stratos independently, rather than pursuing a license from Avanti, reflected both corporate pride and strategic calculation. The Draconis Combine's industrial policy has long favored domestic production over foreign imports, and an Avanti-licensed airliner would have been a difficult sell to Kuritan airlines accustomed to buying Combine-made equipment. Wakazashi's reputation as one of the Combine's premier aerospace manufacturers gave the Stratos instant credibility in a market skeptical of foreign designs.</p><p>The Stratos debuted to respectable reviews, with aviation analysts praising Wakazashi's engineering while noting that the ninety-passenger capacity placed it at a disadvantage against the larger Comet on high-traffic routes. Yet, the WK-1000 carved out a solid niche in the Combine market and demonstrated that Wakazashi could produce more than military hardware and luxury aircraft like the Graceful Crane. The airliner also proved that the Combine's civilian aerospace sector could compete on quality, if not yet on scale.</p>
</history>

